    "reasoning": "Problem 1: We need to find the minimal |P(20) + P(70)| for a polynomial P with integer coefficients satisfying P(0) + P(90) = 2018. Define Q(x) = P(x) + P(90 - x), which is symmetric around x = 45 and has integer coefficients. Thus, Q(x) = R((x - 45)^2) where R has integer coefficients. Given Q(0) = 2018, we have R(2025) = 2018. The value Q(20) = R(625), and since 2025 - 625 = 1400 divides R(2025) - R(625), we get R(625) = 2018 - 1400k for integer k. Minimizing |R(625)| gives k = 2 (R(625) = -782) or k = 1 (R(625) = 618). However, Q(x) must be even for all integer x (since P(x) and P(90 - x) have the same parity), so Q(x) = 2S(x) with S having integer coefficients. Thus, S(2025) = 1009 and S(625) = 1009 - 1400k. The minimal |S(625)| is 391 (k = 1), so minimal |Q(20)| = 782. For P(x) = x² - 90x + 1009 (integer coefficients), P(70) = -391. Thus, m = P(70) + 162 = -391 + 162 = -229.\n\nProblem 2: The key invariant is the parity of the number of green balls modulo 2. Initially, there are 2021 green balls (odd). Each operation either preserves the parity (same-color draw) or flips it (different-color draw). The process ends with 1 ball, so the number of different-color draws k satisfies 4041 - 2k = 1 ⇒ k = 2020 (even). Since k is even, the parity of green balls remains odd (2021 - 2020 = 1 mod 2). Thus, the last ball must be green, so p = 1. Therefore, ⌊2021p⌋ = 2021.",
